      <div id="related-links" class="related-links">
        <h2>Around the Web</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="http://www.vulture.com/2014/01/tv-review-hbos-true-detective.html" target="_blank">
              <h5>The murder mystery is beside the point in HBO’s existentialist cop drama "True Detective"</h5>
              <p>"True Detective" is truly unsettling, not because it’s about the search for a Louisiana serial killer, but because soon enough the search seems almost incidental: a pretext for testing limits and acting out and debating what makes people tick.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> New York Magazine</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/11/arts/television/mcconaughey-and-harrelson-star-in-true-detective-on-hbo.html" target="_blank">
              <h5>If there’s a compelling reason to watch, Matthew McConaughey and Woody Harrelson provide it</h5>
              <p>The series reveals itself as a languid character study and a vehicle for long-winded exchanges about religion and responsibility that are writerly in the worst way.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> The New York Times</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/interview-cary-fukunaga-on-hbo-series-true-detective-starring-matthew-mcconaughey-and-woody-harrelson-20130712" target="_blank">
              <h5>Director Cary Fukunaga on "True Detective"</h5>
              <p>"You have 8 hours of story sitting in your head, and moving pieces around so that when we get to here, will this be clear enough? Do I need to heighten this moment or stretch this one?"</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> IndieWire</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/02/02/writer-nic-pizzolatto-on-thomas-ligotti-and-the-weird-secrets-of-true-detective/" target="_blank">
              <h5>Series writer Nic Pizzolatto on "True Detective"</h5>
              <p>"I read Thomas Ligotti's 'The Conspiracy Against the Human Race' and found it incredibly powerful writing…I’d already been reading E.M. Cioran for years and consider him one of my all-time favorite and, oddly, most nourishing writers."</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> The Wall Street Journal</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/mcconaughey-reveals-the-four-stages-of-true-detective-rustin-cohle-20140304" target="_blank">
              <h5>McConaughey reveals the four stages of "True Detective" Rustin Cohle</h5>
              <p>When Matthew McConaughey was preparing for the psychedelically complex character he plays in "True Detective," he made a monster document to help him find his way.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Rolling Stone</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/her-looming-shadow-grows-the-women-of-true-detective/" target="_blank">
              <h5>Her looming shadow grows: the complex women of "True Detective"</h5>
              <p>"A show that takes up misogyny as one of its main subjects isn’t necessarily misogynistic."</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Molly Lambert, Grantland</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/03/03/cool-story-bro" target="_blank">
              <h5>The shallow deep talk of “True Detective"</h5>
              <p>To state the obvious: while the male detectives of “True Detective” are avenging women and children, every live woman they meet is paper-thin.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Emily Nussbaum, The New Yorker</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.vulture.com/2014/02/true-detective-who-is-the-yellow-king.html" target="_blank">
              <h5>"True Detective": Who is the yellow king? Here are some theories.</h5>
              <p>The knowledge that the Yellow King is a name taken from stories about vaguely supernatural stuff has inspired some grand theoretical leaps.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> vulture.com</p>
            </a>
          </li>
